# Deliverable 4 — Phased roadmap

## Capacity assumptions

Three engineers at roughly 70% effective capacity for project work (the remainder is incidents, on-call rotation, code review, 1:1s, and the things that always slip in). Manager-IC at 45% technical contribution; the remainder is management overhead on a three-person team (weekly 1:1s, planning, stakeholder coordination, occasional hiring loops). Q1 carries an additional overhead tax — onboarding to the codebase, environment setup, first architecture review cycles — so effective Q1 output is closer to 60% than 70%. Approximately 125 engineer-weeks of net output across the year.

---

## Phase 1 — Q1 (months 1–3): Walking skeleton

**Goal:** A single-node ARK deploys from OVA in a VMware lab, bootstraps automatically on first boot, and a test workload installs via a minimal `arkctl` prototype. No HA, no production pipeline, no upgrade system — just the core loop proven end-to-end in a real environment.

**Epics in this phase:** E1 (partial — single-node OS image, cloud-init, bootstrap agent, Zot pre-load), E2 (partial — single-node RKE2 and kube-vip, no HA topology yet), E7 (started — self-hosted runner provisioned, manual OVA build process, not yet automated or signed).

**Entry criteria:** openSUSE MicroOS build approach confirmed; VMware test lab available with network isolation; self-hosted runner hardware provisioned; team has read the full brief and aligned on the architecture spine (RKE2, kube-vip, Zot, Longhorn, module operator).

**Definition of done:** A team member who was not involved in the build deploys the OVA to VMware in a fully air-gapped lab, powers on, watches the system bootstrap to healthy without touching a keyboard, and installs a Hello World container via `arkctl module install`. The entire sequence requires no internet, no DNS, no NTP (unless supplied via OVF property).

**Consciously deferred:** HA multi-node topology, module operator CRD (Q1 uses manual Helm), full CLI suite, upgrade system, Longhorn (local-path only in Q1), security scanning and signing in the pipeline, platform services (ingress, cert-manager, identity).

---

## Phase 2 — Q2 (months 4–6): Platform complete

**Goal:** The full platform is running and production-grade. A Superna module team can start building against the `module.yaml` contract. HA is working. A signed OVA comes out of the automated pipeline. This is the milestone that unblocks parallel work across the rest of the organisation.

**Epics in this phase:** E1 (complete — HA-capable OVA, both GuestInfo and generic OVF datasource, full OVF property schema validated), E2 (complete — 3-node HA, kube-vip failover tested and measured, 2-node topology blocked), E3 (complete — ingress, cert-manager with IP SAN, local identity service), E4 (complete — SupernaModule CRD, operator, `module.yaml` spec, dependency resolution, resource governance, network isolation), E6 (Longhorn for multi-node, local-path for single-node), E7 (complete — automated OVA and bundle build, Snyk scan, cosign signing, syft SBOM, Artifactory staging promotion).

**Entry criteria:** Phase 1 complete and walking skeleton validated by at least one end-to-end test. **Critical gate:** `module.yaml` spec reviewed and signed off by at least one future module team lead before E4 development begins. Getting the spec wrong in Q2 costs the most — module teams building on a wrong contract is the highest-risk integration failure mode in the project.

**Definition of done:** A signed OVA produced by the automated pipeline deploys to a 3-node HA cluster; a control-plane node is powered off; traffic resumes within 30 seconds; a real Superna module (not a Hello World stub) installs, runs, and removes via `arkctl module install/remove`; the Artifactory staging artifact carries a valid cosign signature and attached SBOM.

**Consciously deferred:** Optional identity federation (LDAP/AD/OIDC), NFS CSI driver, local-path → Longhorn storage migration tooling, full `arkctl` suite (diagnose, full cluster commands), upgrade system, Xray continuous CVE monitoring (pipeline scan is in, automated rebuild on CVE is Q3).

---

## Phase 3 — Q3 (months 7–9): Upgrade system and CLI complete

**Goal:** A customer could perform a full in-place upgrade end-to-end. The CLI is complete. Storage migration is available. The system is production-capable for early adopters.

**Epics in this phase:** E8 (upgrade system — checkpointed upgrade, rollback, min-version enforcement, resume-on-failure), E5 (CLI — all commands including `arkctl diagnose` with redaction), E6 (complete — NFS CSI driver, local-path → Longhorn migration tooling), E3 addition (optional identity federation — LDAP/AD/OIDC added to the identity service).

**Entry criteria:** Phase 2 complete. At least one Superna module team has built a real module against the `module.yaml` contract and provided feedback on the spec (this feedback loop is critical — module teams will find gaps that internal testing will not). Upgrade bundle format finalised and agreed before E8 development begins.

**Definition of done:** An upgrade from version N to N+1 completes without data loss on a 3-node cluster; an intentionally interrupted upgrade resumes from the last checkpoint correctly; `arkctl diagnose` produces a complete, redacted bundle that Superna support confirms is sufficient for a real support case; a local-path → Longhorn storage migration runs successfully with data integrity verified.

**Consciously deferred:** Full supply chain security hardening (Xray continuous CVE monitoring and automated rebuild automation), performance validation (minimum VM sizing with real workloads), operator documentation (runbooks, module developer guide), formal security review.

---

## Phase 4 — Q4 (months 10–12): Production readiness

**Goal:** ARK is production-grade, security-reviewed, documented, and ready for first customer delivery. A customer could operate ARK day-to-day without Superna engineering on the phone.

**Focus areas (hardening work, not new epics):** Xray continuous CVE monitoring and automated rebuild pipeline fully operational; performance validation — minimum VM sizing confirmed with actual module workloads; operator runbooks and module developer guide written and reviewed; end-to-end test suite covering all critical paths automated in CI; pre-production trial with first identified customer; formal security review including supply chain audit against SBOM.

**Entry criteria:** Phase 3 complete; first customer identified and pre-production environment available; security review scheduled and scoped.

**Definition of done:** ARK passes a security review including supply chain audit; runs successfully in a customer pre-production environment for a minimum of two weeks without engineering escalation; all operator-facing documentation complete enough for field engineers to support without referring to the engineering team.

**Consciously deferred for future quarters:** Cumulative (long-jump) upgrade bundles, fleet visibility product above ARK, optional telemetry opt-in, additional hypervisor platform testing beyond VMware primary and one OVF fallback.

