## What to cut if Q1 runs two months late

If Q1 slips two months, Phase 2 starts in month 5 instead of month 3. The right move is to drop HA from Phase 2 entirely and defer it to Phase 3.

The reasoning: the module operator (E4) is the highest-leverage item in the plan — it is the contract that every future Superna module team builds against, and the earlier they can start, the more feedback the team gets before the spec calcifies. HA (the multi-node kube-vip topology, etcd quorum validation, Longhorn replication) is important for production, but a single-node deployment is a fully supported first-class shape per the NFRs. An early module team or internal testing cohort can run on single-node through a POC and early integration period.

By cutting HA from Phase 2, roughly three to four weeks of Engineer A's time is recovered. That time goes into E4 (module operator) and E3 (platform services), keeping the module contract on time. HA lands in Phase 3 alongside the upgrade system — still before production readiness, still before first customer delivery.

What does not get cut under any circumstances: the module operator spec review by a future module team before E4 implementation starts; the build pipeline reaching a state where it produces signed artifacts by end of Phase 2; and the single-node walking skeleton being genuinely working (not demo-ware) before Phase 2 begins. These three gates are the ones where cutting corners costs the most downstream.
